2. Make a time series decomposition applying additive and multiplicative models.

Additive Decomposition
# Plot the additive classical decomposition
traffic_tsb %>% 
  model(classical_decomposition(Visitors, type = "additive"))%>% components()%>%autoplot()+theme_light()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

We have computed the trend-cycle element \(\hat{T_t}\), obtained the de-trended series: \(y_t-\hat{T}_t=\hat{S}_t+\hat{R}_t\) . The seasonal component is the average of the de-trended series for each period. In order to check what kind of seasonality we are observing we use the acf() function.

# Plot the autocorrelation plot to check seasonality
par(mar=c(7, 3, 3, 1), cex.lab=0.8, cex.axis=0.8, cex.main=0.8)#graphics
acf(ts(traffic$Visitors), lag.max = 31)# autocorrelation plot

Present the autocorrelation function, which of course in the closest lags shows higher correlation. The spikes we observe are due to the seasonal component in the data which is why we plotted our the ACF function. We can see that the “seasonal” pattern is of weekly kind, because the higher spike is at lag 7. So the seasonal component computed by the classical_decompositionis weekly.

Multiplicative Decomposition
# Plot the multiplicative decomposition
traffic_tsb %>% 
  model(classical_decomposition(Visitors, type = "multiplicative"))%>% components()%>%autoplot()+theme_light()
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

In this case we have computed the de-trended series \(y_t/\hat{T}_t=\hat{S}_t\times \hat{R}_t\). The seasonal component in this case changes in range because of how the elements interact with each other.

Between the two decompositions, the noise remainder elements that originates from the multiplicative contains less peaks than the one generated by the additive decomposition. Moreover, in the additive case the remainder does not look random at all, which would imply that there is autocorrelation in the data the selected process fails to model effectively.

3.Repeat the decomposition using the STL approach.

STL Decomposition
# POLt the default STL decomposition
traffic_tsb %>% model(stl = STL(Visitors))%>% components()%>%autoplot()+theme_light()

# Plot the periodic STL decomposition
traffic_tsb %>%
model(STL(Visitors ~ trend(window = 7) + season(window = "periodic"), robust = TRUE)) %>%
components() %>%
autoplot()

We observe the two alternatives, the former case is the default case, so we are not assuming that the seasonality within the data is going to be constant in its variation in the long run. In fact, in the latter decomposition forcing such assumption by setting the window to periodic, results into a more “noisy” process. The remainder element is much less “busy” in the STL default case.

Which decomposition seems to be most relevant to the data?

Given that the seasonality variation grow in range as the trend increases, a multiplicative decomposition would be most appropriate. When considering the STL decomposition we have to consider the fact that in STL decomposition unless we coerce the seasonal component to “periodic” the seasonal component is not assumed to be constant over time. In fact, the seasonality might change in the future due to some weekly discount the website might implement or some content release day being moved. Yet, when simply comparing the STL default case and the multiplicative classical decomposition, the Rt that appears more random is the multiplicative one. Because of this a good idea, would be to log the data and then model the series once again.

as_tsibble() %>%

dcmp_stl<- traffic_tsb %>% model(stl = STL(Visitors))

as_tsibble() %>%
autoplot(Visitors, colour="#000C4A") +
geom_line(aes(y=trend), colour = "red")+theme_light()

The trend-cycle does not seem to differ across the decompositions in terms of smoothness. But for sure regarding the classical two, we observe that the extremes are missing some data points, which is to be expected because the trend-cycle component is computed with a moving average method, meaning that the first few data-points are missing. For the STL this does not happen, moreover the smoothness of it can be controlled by the user.

Exercise 4

  • What is the reason to apply a moving average to a moving average?

    The use of a MA is the first step of classical decomposition, it allows us to estimate the trend-cycle at time t by taking the average of the series within k periods of t.

    A double MA is used in the case in which the data displays a even periodicity m, that is to make the MA symmetric. For example, is we were to compute the MA of a series with even periodicity, only once, our results would have asymmetric estimates (look at table3.2 of the book).

    By re-applying a MA to it we re-centre the estimates, this happens at \(\hat{T}_{t+1/2}\).

  • Show that a 4x4 MA is a weighted moving average.

    A 4x4MA is equivalent to a 7 weighted MA

    We estimate \(\hat{T}_{t+1/2}=\frac{1}{2k}\sum^{k}_{j=-(k-1)}y_{t+j}\) which is an un-weighted moving average.

    Weighted moving average with even periodicity: \(\hat{T}_{t+1/2}=\sum^{k}_{j=-(k-1)}a_jy_{t+j}\); we would assume symmetric weights so aj=a_-j and that they sum up to 1.

    Weighted moving averages result in a smoother trend-cycle.

    \(\hat{T}_t=\frac{1}{4}(\frac{1}{4}\left(y_{t-3}+y_{t-2}+y_{t-1}+ y_{t}\right)+\\+\frac{1}{4}\left(y_{t-2}+y_{t-1}+y_t+y_{t+1}\right)+\\+\frac{1}{4}\left(y_{t-1}+y_t+y_{t+1}+y_{t+2}\right)+\\+\frac{1}{4}\left(y_t+ y_{t+1}+y_{t+1}+y_{t+3}\right))=\\=\frac{1}{16}y_{t-3}+\frac{2}{16}y_{t-2}+\frac{3}{16}y_{t-1}+\frac{4}{16}y_{t}+\frac{3}{16}y_{t+1}+\frac{2}{16}y_{t+2}+\frac{1}{16}y_{t+3}\)

    \(\hat{T_t}=\\=\frac{1}{7}(y_{t-3}+y_{t-2}+y_{t-1}+y_t+y_{t+1}+y_{t+2}+y_{t+3})]\\=\frac{1}{16}y_{t-3}+\frac{1}{4}y_{t-2}+\frac{1}{4}y_{t-1}+\frac{1}{4}y_{t}+\frac{1}{4}y_{t+1}+\frac{1}{4}y_{t+2}+\frac{1}{16}y_{t+3}\)

    \(\frac{1}{4}[\frac{1}{2k}\sum^{k}_{j=-(k-1)}y_{t+j}]=\sum^{k}_{j=-k}a_jy_{t+j}\)

  • How many terms are involved? Compute the weights.

    The MA is of order 4x4, which means that we average over 4 datapoint moving by 1 step and recomputing the average 4 different times, the terms involved are 7. We have computed the weights above, the last terms take weight 1/(4m).

    The weights have been computed above.

  • For what seasonality can it be applied?

    Could be applied for data measured on a quarterly basis. Of course compared to a 2x4MA the resulting trend-cycle is smoother.

  • Provide two examples from the business world when 4x4 MA is appropriate.

    Companies in the US have to file quarterly financial statements, so all those indices and figures will have to be re-centred when modelled for the generation of forecasts.

    (source: Understanding a Quarterly Financial Report and Its Requirements (investopedia.com) )

    Sales (which in fact are reported cumulatively into financial statements) can be grouped into quarterly groups. Because, of course for daily recorded data we can estimate quarterly statistics.

    ( source: ADIDAS Quarterly Sales Forecasting | Kaggle )
